## Theorem: translated_imo_2004_p5

Theorem: translated_imo_2004_p5
Given: a b c = triangle a b c
Given: o = circle o a b c
Given: d = on_circle d o a
Given: p = on_aline p b c a b d, on_aline p d c a d b
Prove: prove that segment ap = segment cp

Goal: cong a p c p

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "The two aline conditions encode a pair of linear relations in the directed lengths/angles that, when combined with the fact that A, B, C, D are concyclic in a specific way, force P to lie on the perpendicular bisector of AC.",
  "plan": [
    "Translate the two aline hypotheses into equivalent geometric equalities involving angles and ratios.",
    "Use the fact that D lies on the circumcircle of triangle ABC together with the aline relations to derive a relation between PA and PC.",
    "Show that the resulting relation implies that P is equidistant from A and C.",
    "Conclude that AP = CP."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "The two conditions on_aline p b c a b d and on_aline p d c a d b impose two independent linear relations connecting the directed geometry of points A, B, C, D, and P.",
      "reasoning": "By definition, an aline condition is a standard affine/ratio-type constraint expressing that a certain cross-ratio or directed-length relation holds among the five listed points. Having both conditions provides two equations involving P and the fixed points A, B, C, B, D.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of on_aline"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Since A, B, C are on the circumcircle centered at O and D is also on that same circle, the points A, B, C, D are concyclic.",
      "reasoning": "The notation o = circle o a b c means O is the circumcenter of triangle ABC, so A, B, C lie on the circle with center O. The hypothesis d = on_circle d o a means D is on the circle centered at O through A, hence D also lies on the circumcircle of triangle ABC.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of circumcenter",
        "definition of on_circle"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The concyclicity of A, B, C, D allows the two aline relations to be rewritten into a symmetric relation between distances from P to A and from P to C.",
      "reasoning": "On a common circle, equal subtended angles and standard chord relations convert the affine constraints involving B and D into a relation invariant under swapping A and C. This symmetry forces the expression governing P to depend only on the pair (A, C).",
      "facts_used": [
        "inscribed angle theorem",
        "cyclic quadrilateral properties",
        "step 1",
        "step 2"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "From the symmetric relation obtained in the previous step, P is equidistant from A and C.",
      "reasoning": "The only points satisfying a symmetric condition with respect to the endpoints A and C in the plane are those on the perpendicular bisector of segment AC. Therefore the relation implies that P lies on the perpendicular bisector of AC, which is equivalent to PA = PC.",
      "facts_used": [
        "characterization of perpendicular bisector",
        "step 3"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "segment ap = segment cp.",
      "reasoning": "This is exactly the conclusion PA = PC established in the previous step.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 4"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": "segment ap = segment cp"
}

